ublic discourse about femininity to the images of women in propaganda and commercial culture. She analyzes fascist attempts to organize women and the ways in which Mussolini's intentions were received by women as social actors. The first study of women's experience under Italian fascism, this is also a history of the making of contemporary Italian society.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFascismxHistoryx20th centuryxItaly. 0aFascismzItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aFascismexHistoirex20e sièclexItalie. 0aFemmesxHistoirex20e sièclexItalie. 0aFemmesxPolitique gouvernementalexHistoirex20e sièclexItalie. 0aWomenxGovernment policyxHistoryx20th centuryxItaly. 0aWomenxGovernment policyzItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxHistoryx20th centuryxItaly. 0aWomenzItalyxHistoryy20th century. 4aEurope. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh1 aGrazia, Victoria de, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052007457640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091138340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520911383423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520911383/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles